{{about|Belling-Lee connectors as used in TV antenna installations in Europe|an RF connector used in similar applications in other regions|F connector}} {{Infobox connector |name = Belling-Lee connectors |type = [[RF connector|RF coaxial connector]] |image = [[File:IEC 169-2 male and female connector.JPG|250px]] |logo = |caption = Male (left) and female Belling-Lee connectors |designer = Belling & Lee Ltd in Enfield, [[United Kingdom]] |design_date = Around 1922 (Belling-Lee) |manufacturer = |diameter = |width = |height = |electrical = |earth = |maximum_voltage = |maximum_current = |cable = [[Coaxial]] |passband = |physical_connector = }} [[Image:bellingleeconnectorjack.jpg|thumb|Female Belling-Lee connector on a television set.]]
The '''Belling-Lee connector''' (also '''type 9,52''', but largely only in the context of its specification, ''[[International Electrotechnical Commission|IEC]] 61169, Part 2: Radio-frequency coaxial connector of type 9,52'')<ref name=iec61169-2>IEC. "International Standard 61169-2 – Radio-frequency connectors – Part 2: Sectional specification – Radio frequency coaxial connectors of type 9,52". Second edition. Reference number IEC 61169-2-2:2007(E). {{ISBN|9782831889931}}.</ref> is commonly used in Europe and Australia to [[RF connector|connect]] [[coaxial cable]]s with each other and with terrestrial [[VHF]]/[[UHF]] roof [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]s, antenna signal amplifiers, [[CATV]] distribution equipment, [[TV set]]s, and [[FM broadcasting|FM]] and [[Digital Audio Broadcasting|DAB]] [[radio receiver]]s. In these countries, it is known colloquially as a '''PAL antenna connector''', '''IEC antenna connector''', or simply as a '''TV aerial plug'''. It is one of the oldest coaxial connectors still commonly used in consumer devices.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
It was invented at Belling & Lee Ltd in Enfield, [[United Kingdom]] around 1922 at the time of the first BBC broadcasts. Belling Lee Limited still exists as a wholly owned subsidiary of [[Dialight]], since 1992.<ref>http://www.dialight.com/Assets/investorrelations/financialinfo/financialreports/pdf/dialight_ar_2016_final_170316%5B2%5D.pdf (page 117)</ref>
In ''type 9,52'', the ''9,52'', in French SI style, refers to the 9.525{{nbsp}}mm ({{frac|3|8}}, or 0.375{{nbsp}}in) male external and female internal connector body diameter.
In their most common form the connectors just slide together. There is, however, also a screw-coupled variant which is specified to have a M14×1 thread.<ref name=iec61169-2 />
[[Image:J M Briscoe13 05 200714 11 3300596 1 MIN BELLING LEE.jpg|thumb|Regular and miniature Belling-Lee plugs.]] There is also a miniature Belling-Lee connector which was used for internal connections inside some equipment (including BBC RC5/3 Band II receiver and the STC AF101 Radio Telephone). The miniature version is only about {{convert|4.4|mm}} in diameter.
