'''Rule 40''' is a [[by-law]] in the [[Olympic Charter]] stating that only approved sponsors may reference "Olympic-related terms".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/olympics/36909409|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Athletes could face sanctions over controversial rule 40|last=|first=|date=27 July 2016|website=BBC News|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref> It was introduced by the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) to prevent so-called [[ambush marketing]] by companies who are not official sponsors and to sanction links between athletes and unofficial sponsors during a blackout period starting 9 days before the opening of the [[Olympic Games]] and continuing until 3 days after the closing ceremony.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/rio-olympics-rule-40-changes-marketing-summer-games-200732935.html|title=Why the biggest business story of the Rio Olympics is this marketing rule change|last=Roberts|first=Daniel|date=3 August 2016|website=Yahoo! News|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/onmarketing/2016/08/04/sponsorship-and-advertising-trends-in-the-2016-rio-olympic-games-three-things-to-watch-for|title=Sponsorship And Advertising Trends In The 2016 Rio Olympic Games: Three Things To Watch For|last=Taylor|first=Charles R.|date=4 August 2016|website=Forbes|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref>
Controversy sparked in the days before the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] as rule 40 was upheld in an effort to prevent companies from retweeting anything from the official Olympic [[Twitter]] account, or use official hashtags such as #Rio2016 and #TeamUSA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2016/07/28/ioc-bans-social-media-olympics-brands/|title=The Olympic committee wants to ban non-sponsor brands from tweeting about the games|last=Kulp|first=Patrick|website=Mashable|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-36915565|title=Who can't tweet about #Rio2016?|last=|first=|date=31 July 2016|website=BBC News|publisher=|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref> The [[United States Olympic Committee]] (USOC) sent letters to companies sponsoring individual athletes but with no official sponsorship designation with a warning that they might be infringing rights by using such hashtags or other trademarks owned by USOC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/olympics/story/_/id/17120510/united-states-olympic-committee-battle-athletes-companies-sponsor-not-olympics|title=USOC warns non-Olympic sponsor companies|last=Rovell|first=Darren|date=21 July 2016|website=ESPN|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2016/07/27/olympic-committee-may-sue-brands-use-hashtags-images-rio-games/|title=Olympic Committee may sue if brands use hashtags or images from Rio games|last=Swanner|first=Nate|date=2016-07-27|website=The Next Web|publisher=|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-06}}</ref>
